# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agriculture-in-the-united-states
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The **1903 Oxnard strike** was a labor rights dispute in the southern California coastal city of Oxnard between local landowners and the majority Japanese and Mexican labor force.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The interethnic organizing of the strike would presage Oxnard Mexican and Filipino sugar beet worker participation in the California agricultural strike of 1933 and later the efforts of the United Farm Workers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The union would dissolve shortly after the strike, withdrawing their charter request made to the American Federation of Labor, with Mexican workers rejecting AFL President Samuel Gompers' demand for Japanese exclusion.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] In 1887, Henry, James, Benjamin, and Robert Oxnard sold their Brooklyn sugar refinery and moved to California to capitalize on the growing agricultural economy of the late nineteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] In 1897, following the enactment of the Dingley Tariff Bill that heavily taxed foreign sugar, Henry, James, and Robert Oxnard formed the American Beet Sugar Company (ABSC).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] As the ABSC merged its operations with growers, a host of migrant laborers were recruited, with Chinese, Mexican, Japanese, Filipino, Sikh and white laborers procured in various waves.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] In the segregated sections of Oxnard carved out for primarily non-white workers, there was interethnic socialization: in Oxnard's Chinatown (dubbed "China Alley"), billiards halls such as "Yamaguchi's pool room" served as sites of interaction between agricultural workers of different backgrounds.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Many *Issei*, or first-generation Japanese immigrants, moved to California as a result of Meiji-era land reforms which undermined the economic position of many smallholders in the Empire's rural prefectures, as well as political persecution.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] In 1898, the first Japanese work-crew was introduced by Kurihara, setting off a recruitment pattern which raised the Japanese worker population in Oxnard to a thousand the following year.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] By 1902 nine major Japanese contractors saw to the seasonal needs in the area.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Local Japanese residents of Ventura County distinguished themselves from these seasonal laborers, characterizing them as *buranke* *katsugi*, or "blanket carriers".
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] By the turn of the century, the ABSC had attained substantial managerial power over growers, mandating cultivation practices and setting price and wage schedules, and now turned its attention to replacing Japanese and Mexican labor contractors.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Since these contractors had already caused minor slowdowns and protests over wages, recently arrived bank owners and merchants organized an owner-interest oriented contracting company called the Western Agricultural Contracting Company (WACC).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The WACC quickly replaced the Japanese contractors as principal contractors to the Oxnard Plain and even forced some of them to subcontract through the WACC.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Some historians have argued the adeptness of the *keiyaku-nin*—bilingual Japanese labor contractors—at winning high-wage contracts was a significant factor in triggering the WACC's formation.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] This process also adversely affected farmworkers as the WACC charged a fee for subcontracting beneath them.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The WACC regularly refused to pay laborers in cash and instead compensated them with credit for company stores which often sold goods at unreasonably high prices.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Making up more than 90 percent of the work force, the WACC had a near monopoly of the workers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The WACC comprised two distinct departments, one tasked with the oversight of Japanese laborers and labor contractors and another tasked with the oversight of Mexican laborers and labor contractors.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Workers under both of these departments were displeased by the conduct of the WACC.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] As a result, a large group of Japanese farmworkers and labor contractors organized a meeting at the beginning of February 1903 where they discussed their outrage at the working conditions and low wages under the WACC.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] On February 11, 1903, 500 Japanese and 200 Mexican laborers became the charter members of the Japanese-Mexican Labor Association (JMLA) joined together and formed their organization based on the grievances of the Oxnard laborers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Despite its status as a farmworker's labor union, the members of the JMLA were laborers working under contract, labor contractors, and temporary workers - many of whom were students from Japan.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Some union leaders, particularly boarding students, may have been influenced by the socialist movement in Japan.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Many Oxnard *Issei* had arrived from San Francisco and Oakland, where there existed at least two documented Japanese socialist groups, a political tendency which had gained traction in Japan in the wake of the first Sino-Japanese War (1894-95).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Many Japanese and Mexican labor contractors, holding their own grievances against the WACC, backed the JMLA, historically unusual insofar as labor contractors have typically served as suppliers of strikebreakers for employers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The JMLA is notable for being the first major agricultural union in California to unite agricultural workers of different minority groups.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Union leaders employed interpreters to overcome linguistic barriers during strategy sessions, translating Spanish and Japanese while using English as a middle-ground tongue.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Overcoming these barriers, they immediately elected Kosaburo Baba (president), Y.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Yamaguchi (secretary of the Japanese branch), and J.M.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Lizarras (secretary of the Mexican branch); Baba and Lizarras were both labor contractors and Yamaguchi has been recognized as a boarding student recruited from San Francisco.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] In order to remedy these issues, the JMLA membership ceased working through the WACC (essentially declaring a strike).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The strike came at a serendipitously precarious time in the sugar beet season, the staple crop of Oxnard Plain agriculture, since the labor-intensive and yield-defining work of thinning the seedlings needed to be done within the scope of a few weeks.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] By refusing to work through the WACC during the thinning of sugar beet crops, the JMLA challenged the backbone of financial operations in the Oxnard Plain.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Laborers who participated in the strike threatened the profits of the owners of the WACC, the American Beet Sugar Company, and the farm owners.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Their actions were met with hostile responses from local newspapers and the leadership of the American Beet Sugar Company.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Colonel Driffil, manager of the American Beet Sugar Company, formally declared the company's support for the WACC and threatened to drive those who participated in the strike "out of the country".
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Outside of their own membership and other local Mexican and Japanese residents, the JMLA found little support from the white community in Oxnard outside of a few opportunistic merchants who saw the strike as a chance to disrupt WACC operations.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] By the first week in March, the JMLA recruited a membership larger than 1,200 workers (over 90% of the labor force of the county's beet industry).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The JMLA's increased recruitment pulled the WACC's former contracted workers from it and essentially brought the sugar industry to a standstill.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Along with the labor strike, the JMLA staged large demonstrations and marches in Oxnard, displaying the union's strength in numbers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] During the second and third weeks of March, the WACC formed an alternative union known as the Independent Agricultural Labor Union (IALU) which intended to undercut the JMLA's efforts.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The IALU worked with the WACC as a strikebreaking organization seeking to restore regular working conditions in the sugar beet fields rather than advocate for farmworkers' rights.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] On March 23, 1903, the strike reached its turning point.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] During a confrontation between the JMLA and IALU strikebreakers in Oxnard's Chinatown shots were fired, wounding two Japanese and two Mexican members of the JMLA.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Luis Vasquez, a Mexican member of the JMLA, was killed by the gunfire.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Initial reports by local newspapers blamed the JMLA for the violence; however, a statement released by the JMLA in the following days asserted that union members were not armed at the confrontation, pointing out that no union members had been arrested.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The sole arrest from the confrontation was that of Deputy Constable Charles Arnold for the murder of Luis Vasquez.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] After a series of conflicting witness accounts, the county coroner requested that more Japanese witnesses speak at the inquest in the following days.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] However, the all-white male jury refused to continue the inquest as they had reached a verdict with the given evidence.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The jury found Charles Arnold innocent in the murder of Luis Vasquez and he was cleared of all charges.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Despite the outcome of the coroner's inquest, the WACC continued their striking efforts, bringing organized laborers from outside of town as well as intercepting potential strikebreakers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The Ventura *Free Press* reported on an incident in which members of the JMLA confronted a group of strikebreakers headed to a local farm and successfully convinced them to join the union's cause.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] After the deadly skirmish in Chinatown, JMLA representatives met with representatives of local farmers and the WACC to engage in negotiations.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] During the first two days of negotiations, the JMLA stated clearly that they would refuse to end the strike until the WACC ended their monopoly over Oxnard Plain sugar beet operations and allow workers to contract directly with local farmers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The strike reached an official end on March 30, 1903 after the WACC agreed to cancel all standing contracts with local sugar beet farmers and grant farmworkers the right to contract directly with local growers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Japanese and Mexican laborers, formerly pitted against each other, had unified to achieve their labor goals.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] With the WACC as their common enemy, Japanese and Mexican farmworkers recognized their primary struggle as an issue of class conflict.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] JMLA membership viewed Anglo, Mexican, and even Japanese contractors who worked in conjunction with the WACC as antagonists to their cause.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The success JMLA achieved showed the effectiveness of a multi-racial labor front and showed that class and Asian and Mexican shared oppression could be the unifier in labor organizing.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The racial dimensions of the JMLA victory against the WACC brought several issues to the attention of the mainstream American labor movement which traditionally refused to integrate minorities and agricultural workers into unions.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] While certain socialist groups and local factions of organized labor supported the organization of Japanese and Mexican farmworkers, the majority of AFL affiliates and leadership did not support the JMLA.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] This position was mostly based in anti-Asian attitudes and the traditional exclusion of farm laborers from AFL activities.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Following their victory against the WACC, the JMLA sought to charter as the Sugar Beet Farm Laborer's Union of Oxnard (SBFLU) under the American Federation of Labor (AFL).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] However, the JMLA withdrew their request to charter under the AFL after AFL president Samuel Gompers refused to recognize the membership of Asian laborers under the AFL.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The demise of Japanese-Mexican sugar beet unionism is not solely explicable by the SBFLU's rejection of the AFL's racist charter proposal.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Following dissolution of the WACC and its attempts to displace independent Japanese and Mexican labor contractors, contractors shifted from class cooperation to market competition.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Moreover, the demise of WACC led to the disintegration of common cause between the laborers and contractors, the former having their own grievances against the latter as dishonest and exploitative in their own right.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Thirty years after the first strike of *betabeleros* in Oxnard, a second, and unsuccessful, Oxnard strike of sugar beet workers would take place in 1933.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] Two keys to the success of the 1903 strike was the cross-class alliance between laborers and their contractors, and the cross-cultural alliance of Mexican and Japanese laborers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] On the first point, solidarity between contractors and workers did not materialize because the growers' association cut the wage rate, but did not make the WACC's miscalculation of attempting to displace independent contractors.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] On the second point, the ethnic composition of field labor had radically changed: whereas the Japanese workers formed a majority in 1903, Mexican and Mexican-American laborers comprised roughly eighty percent of the 1,200 strikers in 1933, the other twenty percent being Filipino.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1903-oxnard-strike] The growers, in not aggrieving the contractors, did not push them into alliance with the laborers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] The **El Monte berry strike** was a labor strike that began on June 1, 1933, in El Monte, California.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] It was part of the California agricultural strikes of 1933, and like most of them was organized by the Cannery and Agricultural Workers’ International Union (CAWIU).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] By itself, it was one of the largest agricultural strikes in Southern California during the Great Depression, and was the first strike in the season to gain public attention.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] The berry strike affected local Japanese farm owners and growers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] The strike took place in the heart of the Great Depression and eventually involved over 7,000 workers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] Conditions for field workers were difficult.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] The fact that twice as many workers as there were jobs in the San Gabriel Valley caused the walkout as well as bad conditions and low wages.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] Another problem was the inconsistency and insecurity of the wages, which were given based on the number of berries picked: workers probably could not count on having a guaranteed weekly or even daily wage.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] The El Monte Berry Strike brought to light the unique relationship between Mexican and Filipino agricultural workers, Japanese growers, white land owners and local El Monte officials.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] The town of El Monte's land ownership arrangements in 1933 were heavily influenced by the California Alien Land Law of 1913, which dictated who could own land and placed heavy restrictions on immigrants being allowed to own land outright.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] The state of California experienced a heavy influx of Japanese immigrants from 1890 to 1920, which resulted in some immigrants becoming farmowners seeking ownership of land.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] However, California's alien land laws restricted Japanese growers' ownership rights, which led to growers leasing land from local white landowners.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] In 1933, the agreements between Japanese growers and white land lessors were actually in violation of California state law, the strike could have potentially exposed both Japanese lessees and white landowner lessors' land arrangements.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] The situation was profitable for both sides with “roughly 80% of the 600-700 acres of land in El Monte” being leased by Japanese growers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] If local officials could prove there was the possibility of a conspiracy between the white landowners and the Japanese growers, both the Japanese lessee and white landowner stood to lose ownership of the land if local officials enforced the law.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] Tensions between Mexican berry pickers, Japanese growers, white landowners, and local officials were poised to bring unwanted attention to the profitable illegal agricultural arrangements that were in place in El Monte.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] White landowners were also worried that if Mexican and Filipino agricultural workers were successful in striking against their Japanese employers, they would strike against white landowners next.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] Thus, white landowners, the El Monte and Los Angeles Chambers of Commerce, the Los Angeles Police Department, and the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department supported the Japanese farmers in the strike.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] Wages were constantly shifting and the work was insecure, with worker's wages not being guaranteed weekly or even daily.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] Workers were paid per crate of berries, depending on the kind of berries picked.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] Strikers, initially, demanded a raise to a consistent 35 cents per hour (the workday was usually 10–12 hours), which was promptly rejected by Japanese American farmers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] The Japanese countered with an offer of 20 cents per hour, but that was also rejected by the strikers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] Hourly wages prior to the strike were disputed: the Los Angeles Chamber of Commerce placed estimates as high as 25 cents per hour, while workers argued the average was 15 cents and that 9 cents per hour wages were not unusual.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] With no workers to pick fruit during a critical harvest season, Japanese farmers looked for support from organizations within the Japanese community to help pick berries.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] Children were excused from school to help while friends and relatives came from around Southern California to aid in the harvest.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] The El Monte Chamber of Commerce had a vested interest in keeping Mexican and Filipino workers non-unionized and used tactics such as red-baiting to turn public opinion against the strikers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] The Japanese Chamber of Commerce, with the support of the white community, recommended that further participants in Mexican labor strikes be deported, and an entire growing season had been lost with families earning no wages.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] Japanese American farmers in El Monte essentially "won" the strike, but only because their interests overlapped with those of white landowners.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] Furthermore, the defeat of the strikers was part of a larger anti-union campaign.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] The dismal outcome from the strike for agricultural workers resulted in the CAWIU essentially being extinguished by 1934.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-el-monte-berry-strike] Japanese farmers would go on to play a similar middleman role in the Venice celery strike in 1936 and in the rise of the Nisei Farmers League in the 1970s.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Funsten Company, a pecan-processing corporation based in St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis, held a labor strike from May 15 to May 24, 1933.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The workers, consisting largely of black women employed at facilities in both St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis, Illinois, were organized by the Food Workers Industrial Union and were demanding union recognition, an increase in pay, and equal pay for both African American and white American workers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The strike ended in success for the strikers, though within a few years, the union had been crushed by the company.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis had historically been a center for pecan-processing, and in the 1930s, the industry employed about 3,000 people, overwhelmingly black women.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Most worked in nut-picking, the process of removing the edible nut from the shells.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] At Funsten, the largest employer, the black workers earned less and worked longer than their white counterparts.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] In 1933, following several wage decreases, workers began to associate with the local Communist Party USA chapter, which organized the workers under their Trade Union Unity League, which the union was an affiliate of.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] In April of that year, several workers presented demands to management, though after several weeks without an answer, they declared a strike on May 15.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The initial walkout involved about 900 workers, and by the second day, about 200 white workers had joined.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The strike spread to other Funsten facilities, as well as plants owned by other companies, and involved an estimated 1,400 workers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The strikers rejected several compromise offers made by Funsten and maintained support from groups such as the Communist Party and the Unemployed Councils.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Dickmann began to offer arbitration, and on May 24, the union ratified an agreement that saw wage increases near what they had requested.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] In the aftermath of the strike, eleven local unions were formed and enlisted about 1,400 workers, while the Communist Party added about a hundred members.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] While the union was initially successful in preventing downsizing, the company countered by firing certain workers, mechanizing parts of the processing system, and relocating work outside of the Greater St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] By 1935, the union league had been dissolved.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] However, historians have highlighted the strike's impact on labor organizing in the area, citing it as an impetus that led to labor organizing in other industries.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Additionally, several historians have said that the strike foreshadowed other civil rights movements and protests in favor of expanded African American rights.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis has historically been a significant center for the processing of pecans, due in large part to their natural range along the Mississippi River valley and the ease with which they could be transported to and from the city via boat.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] According to historian Clarence Lang, this industry was the city's "major food-processing enterprise".
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis area in the early 1930s, there were 16 factories that processed pecans.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Funsten Company, the single largest employer in the market, which included four in St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis in 1895 by its namesake, a businessman from Virginia.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] By 1933, Funsten's son, Eugene, was the company's president.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] At the time, the company was valued at approximately $75,000 (equivalent to $1.87 million in 2025).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The company's main facility and corporate offices were located at the intersection of Delmar Boulevard and 16th Street.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] In 1933, the pecan processing industry employed about 3,000 women, with Funsten's main plant employing about 700 women.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Industrywide, about 85 to 90 percent of the workforce was made up of black women, with white women constituting much of the remainder.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] With a total of 1,200 employees, Funsten may have been the single largest employer of black women in St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] About 40 percent of these workers were youths, while a majority were middle-aged and had families that they supported.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Only a few men, both African Americans and white Americans, were employed in more specialized positions or as foremen.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] At Funsten, the workers operated in racially segregated facilities.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] For instance, at a plant on Chouteau Avenue, the first floor was where white women worked while the second floor was where black women worked.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Additionally, the black and white workers had different times for arriving and departing from the facilities.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The black women worked 52 hours per week, from 6:45 a.m. to 4:45 p.m.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Monday through Friday, with a 45-minute lunch break.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] White women's schedules, in contrast, typically ran from 7 a.m. to 4:30 p.m., with an hour-long lunch break.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] This was part of a larger trend in the region, as St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis was host to numerous Jim Crow laws that restricted African American life.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Most of the women worked in "picking", a part of the processing procedure where workers would use a knife to separate the edible nut from its nutshell.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The pickers operated in poor working conditions.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Dust from the nuts posed a breathing hazard, which was made worse by poor ventilation in the facilities.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Additionally, despite being a food-related industry, the plants were not subject to health regulations, and bathrooms were often unsanitary.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Sometimes, picking was performed at the workers' houses.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] In the two years preceding 1933, workers at Funsten's facilities experienced multiple wage cuts.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis Star-Times*, one worker who had been a Funsten employee for 18 years, Carrie Smith, stated that, while her average weekly wage in 1918 was $18 ($385 in 2025), she was now making no more than $4 ($99 in 2025).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Another employee stated that she had received weekly wages of as low as $0.63 ($16 in 2025).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] On average, African American workers had a weekly wage of $1.80 ($44.77 in 2025), while white workers had a wage of $2.75 ($68.4 in 2025).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] By contrast, the average weekly wage in 1929 had been about $10 ($187.5 in 2025).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] For pickers, their pay was based on a piece rate, with African Americans getting paid $0.03 per pound of nut-halves and $0.02 per pound of nut-pieces ($0.75 and $0.5 in 2025).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] About half of the Funsten workers at the time were receiving some form of financial assistance.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] In major cities across the United States, the number of families receiving welfare assistance of some form had risen about 85 to 90 percent compared to 1932 due to the impact of the Great Depression.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis, the unemployment rate had risen to about 25 percent the previous year.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Over the course of the Great Depression, unemployment in St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis would peak at about 30 percent, compared to 9 percent prior to the Depression, and roughly 70 percent of black workers were either unemployed or underemployed.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] As a result, the city was a hotbed for radical labor movements, including campaigns to assist the poor.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] African Americans were overrepresented in these movements.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Around 1933, the idea of labor organizing at Funsten originated with a relative of two company employees.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] This man was a member of the Communist Party USA and invited his relatives to attend party meetings.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Within a few meetings, a score of women had met and, working with the Communist Party, began to organize under the Food Workers Industrial Union.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] This union was an affiliate of the Trade Union Unity League, a Communist Party-led labor organization that advocated for industrial unionism.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Their involvement with the nut-pickers marked the union's first involvement in St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] William Sentner, a party associate and member of the local John Reed Club, served as a union organizer; Smith was the "heart and soul" of the labor action.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] According to historian Myrna Fichtenbaum, the organizing efforts most likely first took hold at a Funsten plant in western St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] While there were union members at other plants, this plant boasted a union membership of about 100 workers, representing about half of the plant's workforce.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] On April 24, 1933, a dozen union members at the Easton Avenue plant presented their demands to management, and they were told that their demands would be conveyed up the management chain and that they would get a response soon.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] However, after three weeks had passed without a response from the company, the executive committee decided to initiate further organizing efforts at other Funsten plants.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] On May 12, the union held a meeting with 700 employees at Funsten's main facility and enrolled an additional 15 members into their union.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The following day, the union held a large meeting and conducted a vote on whether to initiate a strike action, with the consensus being to strike.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The union decided that on Monday, May 15, workers at the Easton Avenue plant would ask for a response to their demands and, if the response was unsatisfactory, they would initiate a walkout and inform workers at the main plant to do the same.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] This strike action would follow a previous wildcat strike that had occurred at Funsten's main plant in 1927, which had ended in failure for the strikers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] On May 15, approximately 900 Funsten employees performed a walkout, initiating the strike.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] By the second day, the number of striking workers had grown to about 1,400.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] While only African Americans had been involved in the initial walkout, white workers began to join the strike by the second day.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] By this time, the strike had expanded to two other Funsten plants, as well as the facilities of two other companies: the Central Pecan Company and the Liberty Nut Company.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Following the third day of the strike, the president of Funsten offered the strikers a wage increase of 33+1⁄3 percent, though this offer was rejected by the strikers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Funsten later offered a pay rate of $0.75 ($18.65 in 2025) per 25-pound (11 kg) box of pecans, though this offer was also rejected.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] In justifying his company's position to the press, Funsten stated that the wage cuts had been a result of the economic downturn, highlighting this in an interview with the *St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis Post-Dispatch* where he stated that the company had not made a profit in two years.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis Argus*, an African American newspaper, pushed back against his claims given the current price of pecans, while Fichtenbaum stated that later analysis showed an estimated yearly profit for Funsten of $250,000 at the time.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] At each plant, the workers elected their own strike committees and leaders, with most of the leaders being black women.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The committees held daily meetings to plan strategies, and public meetings were held every morning to keep the strikers informed of any new developments.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Additionally, the strikers organized committees to handle negotiations, as well as relief efforts for the workers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The strikers reached out to the broader community for support, with representatives of the workers participating in meetings at local churches and synagogues.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Food donations were collected from individuals and groups in the area, such as the Communist Party and the Unemployed Councils, with the Workers International Relief office in Chicago making a donation to the effort.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] One of the strike leaders was a middle-aged black woman named Carrie Smith.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Among other contributions to the strike, she created the slogan, "We demand ten and four" in reference to the strikers' desired pay scale.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Strikers picketed outside of the affected facilities, with picket signs bearing slogans such as, "Animals in the Zoo Are Fed While We Starve".
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Protesting began at 5 a.m. every morning and included strikers, their relatives, and other activists from the Communist Party and from the Unemployed Councils.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Concerning this latter group, about 600 members were involved in picketing outside of Funsten's headquarters.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] At some point during the strike, there was a large meeting at the Labor Lyceum, the Communist Party's headquarters in St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis, where workers sang "Solidarity Forever".
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Over the course of the strike, police escorted strikebreakers to the affected plants, resulting in some confrontations with the strikers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] While sources vary on the exact number, at least 90 strikers were arrested in these scuffles.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] During the strike, a biracial group of five women met with the city counselor of St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis at City Hall in order to ask the city government to act as arbitrators between the strikers and management.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] On May 22, about a thousand strikers marched from the Communist Party's headquarters to City Hall, where a rally took place.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis to address the protestors, and he was received with applause as he spoke from the steps of City Hall and said he would meet with some representatives of the strikers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] On May 23, an all-day meeting was held between the central strike committee, Funsten and his attorney, and a committee organized by the mayor.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The mayor's committee was composed of several notable community leaders and had been organized by the mayor to investigate the pay and working conditions at the nut processing facilities.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Additionally, the pay scale would be equal for both black and white employees.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Notably, however, the agreement did not specify that the company had to recognize the union as the employees' bargaining representatives.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] On May 24, Smith and Mayor Dickmann drove from City Hall to the Communist Party's headquarters, where approximately 700 workers had gathered to vote on the agreement.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] In a unanimous vote, the workers present accepted the agreement, bringing the strike against Funsten to an end.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The other nut-processing companies that had been targeted also agreed to the same pay scale.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The strike, which was the first major labor dispute that St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis experienced during the Great Depression, drew national attention.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Multiple nut-processing factories in Greater St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The strike involved about 1,400 workers, with a majority being black women.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Following the labor dispute, several of the former strikers joined the Communist Party, with the party enrolling about 100 African American nut-pickers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] By the end of the year, African Americans constituted approximately one-third of St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Sentner benefitted from the success of the strike, eventually serving as the national director of the Food Workers Industrial Union.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] He would be involved in a number of labor disputes in the Midwestern United States over the next several decades.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Following the strike, roughly 1,400 nut-pickers joined eleven local unions of the Food Workers Industrial Union organized across the Greater St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Around the end of May 1933, a central committee of the union held a meeting with Funsten management where they were able to convince the company to not move forward with a planned downsizing that would have led to a third of the company's workforce getting fired.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Several additional labor disputes arose over the next several months regarding other issues faced by the nut-pickers, including allegations that they were being cheated out of their deserved wages and a decision by the management at one Funsten plant to not enforce a closed shop.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Shortly after the labor dispute had ended, the Funsten company commenced plans to relocate their nut-processing operations to other areas in the Southern United States.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] In September 1933, the company made a significant downsizing in their St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis operations and later closed three facilities in East St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The union was further weakened by targeted firings of some of the more militant employees at Funsten and through the implementation of mechanization processes in their plants.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Processing work was relocated to San Antonio in Texas, a state where wages were lower than in the St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] By 1934, much of Funsten's processing work was being performed outside of Greater St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] By this time, according to Lang, "the union was at best on the defensive, and at worst in a state of decline".
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] By the 1970s, Funsten had become a subsidiary of Pet, Inc.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Multiple commentators have stated that the initial successful outcome of the Funsten strike inspired future labor disputes in other fields.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Both Fichtenbaum and labor historian Philip S.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Foner drew a direct link between the Funsten strike and strikes involving garment and laundry workers in St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis and Chicago that occurred later in the year.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Later, the TUUL, under their Marine Workers Industrial Union, helped organize a walkout of levee workers in St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The nut-pickers' strike also inspired the St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis chapter of the National Urban League (which had opted to not officially endorse the strikers) to become more attentive to the working conditions of black women.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Meanwhile, Mayor Dickmann appointed an attorney to inspect the working conditions at numerous factories in St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis and make reports back to the mayor's office.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Writer Jack Conroy, who was an acquaintance of Sentner's through the John Reed Clubs, incorporated elements of the strike into his 1935 novel *A World to Win*.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] In her history of the strike, Fichtenbaum stated that the historical contributions of black women to the labor movement had been largely neglected.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] In a commentary on the role of black women in Communist Party activities in St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis, Lang stated, "The emphasis on industrial strongmen in Communist iconography ... implicitly devalued black women's particular issues around work and living conditions".
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Several commentators have noted that the nut-pickers' strike presaged later civil rights activism.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Feurer notes that, following the strike, there was a push in St.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Louis among African American activists for a "Bill of Rights for Negroes" that preceded the civil rights movement of the mid-20th century.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] The bill, which was advocated for by leadership of the Food Workers Industrial Union, sought to bar racial discrimination in housing and employment, among other areas.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-funsten-nut-strike] Discussing the long-term impact of the strike in 2023, historian Keona Ervin said, "I think it's so critical to draw this genealogy of black women's working-class radicalism and to demonstrate this larger history that is a living one.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] The **1933 Wisconsin milk strike** was a series of strikes conducted by a cooperative group of Wisconsin dairy farmers in an attempt to raise the price of milk paid to producers during the Great Depression.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] Three main strike periods occurred in 1933, with length of time and level of violence increasing during each one.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] The cooperative milk pool attempted to coordinate their efforts with larger farm groups, specifically the National Farm Holiday Association and Wisconsin Farmers' Holiday Association.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] However, during each strike, the larger farm holiday groups ended their strikes prematurely, leaving the milk pool to conduct its strike alone.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] The price of evaporated milk from 1927 to 1929 was $4.79 per 100 lbs., with 46% going to farmers, 33% to manufacturers and 21% to merchandisers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] Between 1930 and 1933 the price fell to an average of $3.48 per 100 lbs., with individual farmers receiving a smaller percentage of the proceeds: 30.5% to farmers, 43% to manufacturers and 26.5% to merchandisers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] This decrease put small farmers in an extremely difficult position.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] Farmers who produced milk for bottling were able to remain solvent, but those who produced milk for cheese, butter, and other uses were driven into poverty.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] The price of milk that was going to urban areas for bottling was around $1.50 for a hundred pounds while the milk going to cheese and butter factories was only $0.85 for a hundred pounds of milk.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] This created a kind of civil war between the two types of dairy farmers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] Milk to be bottled was largely unaffected by the strikes.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] In the 1930s, Wisconsin was the largest producer of milk in the United States.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] According to the 1930 decennial census, there were more than 125,000 dairy farms in the state.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] 63% of all land in Wisconsin was farmland and 71% of that land was used for dairy farming.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] Methods employed in the strikes were initially to simply not sell milk unless a previously agreed upon price of $1.50 per hundred pounds had been met.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] When the strikers realized they were grossly outnumbered and that some of their members were selling at a reduced price, they resorted to roadblocks to prevent milk deliveries to the manufacturers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] Fixed road blocks were established and trucks were turned back if they contained milk.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] If they refused to turn back, the strikers forcibly dumped the milk at the roadside.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] In the early strikes, the deliveries simply took alternate routes to avoid the fixed roadblocks.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] During later strikes, the strikers took to the roads in search of delivery trucks and forced them to turn back as they were found.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] When they couldn't stop the deliveries, the strikers sometimes resorted to tainting the delivered milk with kerosene or oil, or in a few cases, throwing bombs at the creameries.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] The state attempted to get milk to market by breaking up the road blocks or escorting convoys carrying milk to their destinations.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] Tear gas was employed to disburse larger groups of strikers and in one instance guardsmen with fixed bayonets forced farmers from their position.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] Railways and interurban trains were used to bypass the roadblocks, but some rail lines were blocked by strikers and at least one freight yard was infiltrated resulting in the dumping of the milk in the yard.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] At this time there were other farmer organizations in different Mid-Western states that had already been protesting the rise in dairy prices and other farm problems.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] These farmer leagues had a lot to do with the "Farmers Holiday" organization that emerged in 1932 and 1933 in certain areas that worked with another organization called The United Farmers League that was a communist led group formed in 1930 and 1931 and worked with Farmers Holiday.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] The Farm Holiday Association had done strikes related to other areas of agriculture and related industries such as strikes on livestock in different states and trying to keep farmers in different states on the same side of boycotts and protests.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] Farmers Holiday had a larger impact in the Wisconsin milk strikes by doing milk strikes in other states around the same time and attempting to coordinate strikes to be more effective across state lines targeting certain cities.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] The first set of strikes ran from February 15 to 22.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] They were mainly confined to strike strongholds and centered on the area controlled by the Wisconsin Cooperative Milk Pool, led by Walter M.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] The first blood shed in the strike was reported to be near Appleton, Wisconsin, when milk convoy guards threw heavy objects like horse shoes at a group of 100 strikers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] The second in the series of strikes ran from May 13 to 19.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] These strikes spread to a larger part of Wisconsin and resulted in more violence than the February strike.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] In Shawano County, 30 people were injured when the National Guardsmen, sworn in as deputies and charged with keeping the roads open against the pickets "engaged in a pitched battle" in front of a dairy plant.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] National Guardsmen with fixed bayonets and tear gas forced pickets from Durham Hill in Waukesha County, May 16, 1933.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] 25,000 pounds (11,000 kg) of milk was deliberately tainted with kerosene at a creamery near Farmington in Jefferson County.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] On May 16, a guardsman shot two teenagers, killing one of them, after they failed to stop their vehicle in Racine County.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] On May 18, a farmer in his 50s was killed when he fell or was pushed from the running board of a milk delivery truck after it left a picket road block between Saukville and Grafton in Ozaukee County.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] On May 19, the milk pool began a temporary peace with the state government in Madison to discuss options to end the strikes.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] The third series of strikes ran from October 21 to November 18 and a larger portion of Wisconsin was affected by them.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] Creameries near Plymouth and Fond du Lac, Wisconsin were bombed around November 1, 1933.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] A cheese factory near Belgium, Ozaukee County, Wisconsin was dynamited and burned by the 4th of the week.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] Creameries in Krakow and Zachow, in Shawano County, Wisconsin, were bombed on Friday, November 3, 1933.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] In all, seven creameries were bombed and thousands of pounds of milk were dumped.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] On October 28, 1933, a 60-year-old farmer was killed at a picket line in the Town of Burke after a single bullet was fired into the crowd by a passenger in a car stopped by the crowd.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] The farmer had not been part of the picket and was there delivering food to the strikers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] The shooter had been angered over a headlight a striker had broken while the shooter's vehicle was running the picket line earlier in the night.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] The shooter was later sentenced to two to four years in prison after pleading guilty to manslaughter charges.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] Local newspapers reported that farmers lost $10 million during the strikes.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] After 1933, Singler's Cooperative Milk Pool purchased creameries to help increase the profits of its members, but the milk pool later faded into obscurity.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-wisconsin-milk-strike] The economy eventually improved, helping smaller farmers to earn more money, but it is not clear if the strikes aided this recovery.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The **1933 Yakima Valley strike** (also known as the **Congdon Orchards Battle**) took place on 24 August 1933 in the Yakima Valley, Washington, United States.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] It is notable as the most serious and highly publicized agricultural labor disturbance in Washington history and as a brief revitalization of the Industrial Workers of the World in the region.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] Since 1916, the Yakima Valley had felt the presence of the Industrial Workers of the World (IWW, or Wobblies), which positioned itself in conflict with local authorities and business interests.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The Yakima strikes began with hop pickers in the Yakima Valley.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The demands of the hop pickers were not of anything uncommon during the 1930s, with striking for regular eight-hour work days, the end of child labor in the yards, and a minimum wage of 35 cents per hour for men and women alike.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] At the time, the current rate for common labor was 10 to 12 cents an hour, with hop farmers claiming that they could not pay any more than 12 ½ cents per hour for labor due to lack of profit they made in sales.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] In 1932, Yakima Valley hops sold for 11 to 14 cents a pound.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] Then, effective 7 April 1933, Congress legalized 3.2 percent beer and wine.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] States rapidly moved to repeal the Eighteenth Amendment.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The effect of these events on hop prices was dramatic: in April and May, Valley papers reported sales of the remaining uncommitted 1932 crops at 40 to 50 cents; the Yakima Morning Herald for nearly a month showed prices up to 75 cents per pound.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The forthcoming crop for 1933 commanded 20 to 30 cents.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] Three- and four-year contracts were being signed for 18 to 25 cents.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] On the second day of the strike, the Yakima County Sheriff called the Washington State Patrol to send aid in which resulted in twenty-two officers coming to the aid of the Yakima County Sheriff's office by the next morning.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] Although eight picketers were arrested, it did not discourage picketers from continuing their activities.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The IWW attorney had contacted the hop growers to see if he could bring about a peaceful settlement to the strike, but the hop growers never responded to the attorney.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The strike had fizzled out with little success when matched against the hop growers, sheriffs, and state patrolmen, especially with the Yakima Chamber of Commerce giving the law enforcement and business owners' their support.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] In order to ensure that peace was maintained on the hop farms, Chief Criminal Deputy H.T.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] "Army" Armstrong persuaded local growers to enforce a "night hop patrol" in which at least six men would be on patrol at all times during the harvest in order to protect the fields from sabotage.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The Yakima Valley was an important hops and apple district; many men would travel to the valley during the summer seeking work.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] After the men were laid off due to being transient workers, they became provoked to strike in regards to the lack of work offered, in which farmers responded by creating vigilante bands around the orchards.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] On August 14, several dozen men assembled at the Sunnyside Canal Bridge near the lower valley community of Sawyer.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] Some entered the orchard of Anna Mitchell where they talked to peach pickers about wages.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] While some protestors were reaching out to the pickers working at the orchard farms, others held their position on the bridge to try to dissuade the pickers from crossing the bridge to work for the farmers on the north side of the canal.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] With word spreading quickly of the protestors at the bridge, farmers gathered in order to out-number the strikers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] Both sides had armed themselves with homemade clubs or tree limbs.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The protest turned physical when protestors refused to remove themselves from the bridge.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] Farmers banded together to throw protestors over the bridge in to the canal to "cool them off" in order to calm down the protestors.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] Seeing as the farmers were well-organized and prepared for strikes, along with having the county sheriffs and state patrolmen coming to their aid, the protests of 15 and 16 August were a complete failure.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The IWW and the pickers reached the peak of their strike on 23 August 1933 when several hundred workers gathered in Selah, elected a strike committee of seven members, and demanded an eight-hour day plus 50 cents an hour.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] They also voted for a strike at eleven o'clock the next day.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] In the early morning hours of August 24, about twenty picketers gathered at the Selah ranch and sixty at another, but local farmers and sheriffs patrolled the area in order to keep the pear harvest in operation.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] At about 11:00 am, a group of sixty to one hundred picketers gathered at the large Congdon Orchards ranch, three miles west of Yakima, where pears were being picked.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The men carried signs which advocated striking and discouraged "scabbing." Two sheriff deputies were called, and they told the pickets to move on.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The picketers left the orchard, some to continue to picketing along the road and others to gather at the grassy and tree-shaded triangle of land in the middle of the intersection of what is today Nob Hill and 64th avenues.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] Farmers within a ten-mile radius started calling other farmers to let them know about the picketing that had taken place and to rally up farmers to resist the pickers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The farmers began to walk the picketers still hanging around the orchards towards the town, specifically "The Triangle".
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] Once the picketers were in that area, the farmers insisted that Triangle was private property and demanded that the workers immediately vacate it.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The strikers complied, moving on to the highway.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] Yet, as soon as they did so, the farmers voiced an object to their being congregated on public property.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] Although it is not clear who struck the first blows, apparently several farmers stepped forward and told the picketers to move out of the area.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] There was a brief discussion, then violence broke out.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The bloody altercation involved 250 vigilantes and 100 picketers; of those 100 picketers, 61 workers were taken to the county jail.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The strike was broken up on the night of August 24 due to the Washington National Guard breaking up a protest meeting with tear gas.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] As well, public assemblies were banned and highways and trains were searched for transients.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] National Guardsmen destroyed all the transient camps and hobo jungles in the vicinity.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] A public stockade of heavy timbers and barbed wire was erected to hold the prisoners awaiting trial.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] On two occasions, local vigilante committees seized prisoners as they were released, took them miles into the country, and beat them; once, the vigilantes tarred and feathered their victims and put linoleum cement in their shoes before freeing them.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The prisoners were charged with criminal syndicalism, later changed to vagrancy.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] At the trial on December 17, 1933, twelve men eventually pleaded guilty to vagrancy and agreed not to take civil action against the county, while non-resident Wobblies promised to leave the county for at least one year; in return, Yakima authorities dropped all other charges.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1933-yakima-valley-strike] The Yakima repression "utterly smashed" the strike and agricultural unionism in the Valley, but the wooden stockade remained on the county courthouse grounds until 1943 as a "silent reminder to future malcontents that the spirit of 1933 remained alive in the region".
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1936-venice-celery-strike] The **1936 Venice celery strike** was a labor action in Venice, California (in Los Angeles County) that lasted from April 20, 1936 to May 27, 1936.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1936-venice-celery-strike] The strikers were Mexican American, Filipino American, and Japanese American farmworkers, organized as the Filipino Federated Workers Union, the American Agricultural Industrial Workers, and the Japanese Farm Workers Union of California.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1936-venice-celery-strike] They were employed by Japanese American farmers who had no legal right to own their own land, which was held in the name of various banks (especially Bank of America) and leased to the resident alien farmers to get around the exclusion laws that prohibited Japanese American land ownership.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1936-venice-celery-strike] The "considerable violence" was mostly the work of the LAPD Red Squad, which "used brutal and violent tactics to punish strikers and their supporters".
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1936-venice-celery-strike] There was, however, an incident in Torrance on May 25, in which one young strikebreaker reported that he "was one of 25 men who had been brought to section from Chula Vista to replace striking celery workers" and had been "set upon by Mexicans and Filipinos".
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1936-venice-celery-strike] Much of that violence occurred in the San Joaquin Valley during a series of agricultural strikes that took place in 1933.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1936-venice-celery-strike] The celery strike concluded with workers winning a modest wage increase and other concessions, in an agreement that was later renewed twice.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] The **1938 San Antonio pecan shellers strike** was a labor strike involving 12,000 pecan shellers in San Antonio, Texas, United States.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Considered the largest labor strike in San Antonio's history, it saw mainly Mexican American pecan shellers, organized by labor activist Emma Tenayuca, protest wage cuts by the Southern Pecan Shelling Company.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Starting on January 31, the strike lasted until March 8, when the two sides agreed to arbitration that led to a wage increase for the pecan shellers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] During the 1930s, 40% of the pecan crop in the United States was grown in Texas, with half of that being produced within a 250-mile radius of San Antonio.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Described as the "world's largest pecan shelling center", between 10,000 and 20,000 workers, primarily Mexican American women, worked as shellers, removing the hard outer shell of pecans grown and collected in the region.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Many of them worked in poor conditions for low pay.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] The average weekly family income for pecan shellers was between $1.00 and $4.00, with many shellers having to supplement their seasonal income with additional farm labor.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Additionally, the workrooms were often cramped centers often lacking proper ventilation, running water, and tools for shelling, with many of the shellers having to use their hands to shell the pecans.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] An increased rate of tuberculosis among the shellers was also pinned on the lack of proper ventilation and an abundance of pecan particulates in the workrooms.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] In the 1930s, the Southern Pecan Shelling Company, owned by Julius Seligman, dominated the pecan shelling industry both in San Antonio and nationwide, shelling between one-fourth and one-third of the total national output of pecans.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] This company, like many others in the area, utilized a contract system whereby he sold contractors whole pecans at $0.10 per pound and purchased back the fully shelled pecans at $0.30 to $0.36 per pound, with the contractors handling all labor issues and facilitating the shelling facilities needed.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] In 1933, Seligman hired Magdaleno Rodríguez to organize a company union, the Pecan Shelling Workers' Union.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] However, this union was short-lived, and in 1937 its remnants were reorganized into the Texas Pecan Shelling Workers' Union, supported by the Communist Party of America, who appointed Albert Gonsen as its leader.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] That same year, the United Cannery, Agricultural, Packing, and Allied Workers of America (UCAPAWA), affiliated with the Committee for Industrial Organization (CIO), granted a charter to the San Antonio pecan shellers with the understanding that the union would include other labor groups.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] This included the San Antonio branch of the Workers Alliance of America, founded a year prior by Emma Tenayuca to help assist the pecan shellers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] On January 31, 1938, contractors for the Southern Pecan Shelling Company announced a pay cut for pecan shellers from $0.07 to $0.06 per pound for shelled pecan halves and $0.06 to $0.05 per pound for shelled pecan pieces.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Wages for pecan crackers were reduced from $0.50 to $0.40 per one hundred pounds of pecans.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Following this, 12,000 shellers, or approximately two-thirds of the workforce, spontaneously walked out.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] This was not the first strike action taken by the pecan shellers, as mass strikes had occurred previously in 1934 and 1935 over wage cuts, with both ending without success.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Initially, the faction of the Pecan Shellers' Union organized around Gonsen were unsupportive of the strike, but the UCAPAWA offered its support for the strikers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Tenayuca shortly emerged as the leader of the movement, with the strikers electing her as their committee chair.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] While Tenayuca was not a pecan sheller, she was well known among the pecan shellers for her organization and activism in the Workers Alliance, which Tenayuca claimed had over 10,000 members at the time.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Covering the incident, *Time* reportedly highlighted Tenayuca's communist philosophy and painted her as the puppeteer behind the strike.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Quin and other public officials also employed red-baiting to draw public support away from the strikers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] This strategy largely succeeded, as many moderates spoke out about the strike's perceived communist influence.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] In an interview with the *San Antonio Light*, the police chief argued that there was no strike and that the incident was part of a ploy by communists and not sanctioned by the CIO.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Roman Catholic Archbishop of San Antonio Arthur Jerome Drossaerts also spoke out against the strike and praised efforts by the police.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] However, *La Prensa*, a major Hispanic newspaper in the city, was sympathetic to the strikers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Over the course of the strike, hundreds of protestors and picketers were arrested and imprisoned by the police, including Tenayuca.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Additionally, all soup kitchens in the city were closed to the strikers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] As tensions increased, Texas governor James V.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Allred ordered an investigation into possible violations of civil liberties, with a meeting held on February 14 chaired by the assistant state attorney.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] While the commission found that the police had overstepped their authority, no actions were taken against them.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Concurrently, there were calls from within the UCAPAWA for Tenayuca to step down from her position as strike leader due to concerns about her communist affiliation.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Ultimately, Tenayuca agreed to step down, and she was replaced by UCAPAWA president Donald Henderson.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Speaking of the incident years later, Tenayuca expressed frustration and resentment towards the push to remove her, but she did for the greater good of the movement.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] After her removal, Tenayuca continued to support the strike in less prominent ways.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Around this same time, the strikers received support from several sources.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Texas Representative and future Mayor of San Antonio Maury Maverick stated his support for the strike.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] The American Civil Liberties Union also began to offer help to the strikers, and a rally was held on March 19 at Military Plaza to celebrate the release of some imprisoned strikers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] By March, both sides had agreed to resolve the labor dispute through arbitration.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] On March 8, the pecan shellers returned to work as the union and pecan companies agreed to arbitration via a three-person panel that included Austin, Texas mayor Robert Thomas Miller.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] The panel returned its decision on April 13, mandating a one-half cent increase in wages from the previous rates.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Furthermore, the UCAPAWA local was recognized as the only legal representative for the pecan shellers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] The wage increase decided by the arbitration panel was considered more favorable to the employers than to the shellers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] However, these wages were increased in October following the implementation of the Fair Labor Standards Act of 1938, which instituted a $0.25 minimum wage.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Fearing that this wage increase would lead to mechanization, both the union and pecan companies appealed to have the pecan shellers exempted from the minimum wage requirement, which was ultimately denied.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Following this, the pecan shelling industry turned to mechanization, and by 1941 approximately 10,000 shellers permanently lost their jobs, though many found new employment as the United States mobilized for World War II.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Following the strike, Maverick, who had lost reelection for the House of Representatives, successfully ran for mayor of San Antonio in 1938, with major support from Mexican Americans in the city.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/1938-san-antonio-pecan-shellers-strike] Tenayuca would later write a political essay, "The Mexican Question in the Southwest", that discussed the strike, Tenayuca's politics, and issues facing Mexican Americans in the southwestern United States.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Agricultural activity is particularly concentrated in the Central Valley of California and the Great Plains.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The Great Plains are a vast expanse of flat arable land in the center of the nation covering an area west of the Great Lakes and east of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The eastern wetter half is a major corn and soybean-producing region known as the Corn Belt, and the western drier half is known as the Wheat Belt because of its high rate of wheat production.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The Central Valley of California produces fruits, vegetables, and nuts.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The American South has historically been a large producer of cotton, tobacco, and rice, but it has declined in agricultural production over the past century.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Florida leads the nation in citrus production and is the number two producer of oranges in the world behind only Brazil.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The U.S. has led developments in seed improvement, such as hybridization, and in expanding uses for crops from the work of George Washington Carver to bioplastics and biofuels.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The mechanization of farming and intensive farming have been major themes in U.S. history, including John Deere's steel plow, Cyrus McCormick's mechanical reaper, Eli Whitney's cotton gin, and the widespread success of the Fordson tractor and the combine harvester.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Modern agriculture in the U.S. ranges from hobby farms and small-scale producers to large commercial farms that cover thousands of acres of cropland or rangeland.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Corn, turkeys, tomatoes, potatoes, peanuts, and sunflower seeds constitute some of the major holdovers from the agricultural endowment of the Americas.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Colonists had more access to land in the colonial United States than they did in Europe.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The organization of labor was complex including free persons, slaves and indentured servants depending on the regions where either slaves or poor landless laborers were available to work on family farms.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] European agricultural practices greatly affected the New England landscape.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Colonists brought livestock over from Europe which caused many changes to the land.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Grazing animals required a lot of land and food and the act of grazing itself destroyed native grasses, which were being replaced by European species.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] New species of weeds were introduced and began to thrive as they were capable of withstanding the grazing of animals, whereas native species could not.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The practices associated with keeping livestock also contributed to the deterioration of the forests and fields.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Colonists would cut down the trees and then allow their cattle and livestock to graze freely in the forest and never plant more trees.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The animals trampled and tore up the ground so much as to cause long-term destruction and damage.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Soil exhaustion was a huge problem in New England agriculture.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Farming with oxen did allow the colonist to farm more land but it increased erosion and decreased soil fertility.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] This was due to deeper plow cuts in the soil that allowed the soil more contact with oxygen causing nutrient depletion.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In grazing fields in New England, the soil was being compacted by the large number of cattle and this did not give the soil enough oxygen to sustain life.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In the United States, farms spread from the colonies westward along with the settlers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In cooler regions, wheat was often the crop of choice when lands were newly settled, leading to a "wheat frontier" that moved westward over the course of years.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Also very common in the antebellum Midwest was farming corn while raising hogs, complementing each other especially since it was difficult to get grain to market before the canals and railroads.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] After the "wheat frontier" had passed through an area, more diversified farms including dairy cattle generally took its place.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Warmer regions saw plantings of cotton and herds of beef cattle.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In the early colonial South, raising tobacco and cotton was common, especially through the use of slave labor until the Civil War.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] With an established source for labor, and the development of the cotton gin in 1793, the South was able to maintain an economy based on the production of cotton.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] By the late 1850s, the South produced one-hundred percent of the 374 million pounds of cotton used in the United States.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The rapid growth in cotton production was possible because of the availability of slaves.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In the northeast, slaves were used in agriculture until the early 19th century.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In the Midwest, slavery was prohibited by the Freedom Ordinance of 1787.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The introduction and broad adoption of scientific agriculture since the mid-19th century contributed to economic growth in the United States.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Soybeans were not widely cultivated in the United States until the early 1930s, and by 1942 it became the world's largest soybean producer, due in part to World War II and the "need for domestic sources of fats, oils, and meal".
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Between 1930 and 1942, the United States' share of world soybean production grew from 3% to 47%, and by 1969 it had risen to 76%.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] By 1973 soybeans were the United States' "number one cash crop, and leading export commodity, ahead of both wheat and corn".
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Although soybeans developed as the top cash crop, corn also remains as an important commodity.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] As the basis for "industrial food," corn is found in most modern day items at the grocery store.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Aside from items like candy and soda, which contain high fructose corn-syrup, corn is also found in non-edible items like the shining wax on store advertisements.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Significant areas of farmland were abandoned during the Great Depression and incorporated into nascent national forests.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Later, "Sodbuster" and "Swampbuster" restrictions written into federal farm programs starting in the 1970s reversed a decades-long trend of habitat destruction that began in 1942 when farmers were encouraged to plant all possible land in support of the war effort.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In the United States, federal programs administered through local Soil and Water Conservation Districts provide technical assistance and partial funding to farmers who wish to implement management practices to conserve soil and limit erosion and floods.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Farmers in the early United States were open to planting new crops, raising new animals and adopting new innovations as increased agricultural productivity in turn increased the demand for shipping services, containers, credit, storage, and the like.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Although four million farms disappeared in the United States between 1948 and 2015, total output from the farms that remained more than doubled.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The number of farms with more than 2,000 acres (810 ha) almost doubled between 1987 and 2012, while the number of farms with 200 acres (81 ha) to 999 acres (404 ha) fell over the same period by 44%.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Farm productivity increased in the United States from the mid-20th century until the late-20th century when productivity began to stall.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] From 1986 to 2018 about 30 million acres of cropland were abandoned.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In addition to smaller productions of other agricultural products, such as melon (872), pumpkin (683), grapefruit (558), cranberry (404), cherry (312), blueberry (255), rye (214), olive (138), and others.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Other crops appearing in the top 20 at some point in the last 40 years were: tobacco, barley, and oats, and, rarely: peanuts, almonds, and sunflower seeds.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Alfalfa and hay would both be in the top ten in 2003 if they were tracked by FAO.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Note alfalfa and hay are not tracked by the FAO and the production of tobacco in the United States has fallen 60% between 1997 and 2003.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Heavily mechanized, U.S. agriculture has a high yield relative to other countries.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Goats, horses, turkeys and bees are also raised, though in lesser quantities.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Inventory data is not as readily available as for the major industries.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] For the three major goat-producing states—Arizona, New Mexico, and Texas—there were 1.2 million goats at the end of 2002.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] There were 5.3 million horses in the United States at the end of 1998.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] There were 2.5 million colonies of bees at the end of 2005.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Farm type is based on which commodities are the majority crops grown on a farm.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] One characteristic of the agricultural industry that sets it apart from others is the number of individuals who are self-employed.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Frequently, farmers and ranchers are both the principal operator, the individual responsible for successful management and day-to-day decisions, and the primary laborer for his or her operation.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] For agricultural workers that sustain an injury, the resultant loss of work has implications on physical health and financial stability.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The United States has over 14,000 certified organic farms, covering more than 5 million acres, though this is less than 1% of total US farmland.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The output of these farms has grown substantially since 2011, and exceeded US$7.5 billion in 2016.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Agriculture in the United States is primarily governed by periodically renewed U.S. farm bills.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Governance is both a federal and a local responsibility with the United States Department of Agriculture being the federal department responsible.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Government aid includes research into crop types and regional suitability as well as many kinds of federal government subsidies, price supports and loan programs.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] U.S. farmers are not subject to production quotas and some laws are different for farms compared to other workplaces.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Labor laws prohibiting children in other workplaces provide some exemptions for children working on farms with complete exemptions for children working on their family's farm.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Children can also gain permits from vocational training schools or 4-H clubs which allow them to do jobs they would otherwise not be permitted to do.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] A large part of the U.S. farm workforce is made up of migrant and seasonal workers, many of them recent immigrants from Latin America.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Additional laws apply to these workers and their housing which is often provided by the farmer.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Farmworkers in the United States have unique demographics, wages, working conditions, organizing, and environmental aspects.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] According to The National Institute for Occupational Safety & Health in Agricultural Safety, approximately 2,112,626 full-time workers were employed in production agriculture in the US in 2019 and approximately 1.4 to 2.1 million hired crop workers are employed annually on crop farms in the US.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] A study by the United States Department of Agriculture found the average age of a farmworker to be 33.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In 2017, the Department of Labor and Statistics found the median wage to be $23,730 a year, or $11.42 per hour.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The types of farmworkers include field crop workers, nursery workers, greenhouse workers, supervisors, etc.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The United States Department of Labor findings for the years 2019-2020 report that 63 percent of crop workers were born in Mexico, 30 percent in the mainland United States or Puerto Rico, 5 percent in Central America, and 2 percent in other regions.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The amount of farm labor in the United States has changed substantially: in 1870, almost 50 percent of the U.S. population was employed in agriculture; as of 2008, less than 2 percent of the population is directly employed in agriculture.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Potential health and safety issues that may be associated with farm work include vehicle rollovers, falls, musculoskeletal injuries, hazardous equipment, grain bins, pesticides, unsanitary conditions, and respiratory disease.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] According to the United States Department Of Labor, farmworkers are at risk of work-related lung diseases, noise-induced hearing loss, skin diseases, and certain cancers related to chemical use.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Farm workers also suffer disproportionately from heat stress, with fewer than average seeking treatment.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] While some progress has been made, many farmworkers continue to struggle for fair pay, proper training, and safe working conditions.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Agriculture ranks among the most hazardous industries due to the use of chemicals and risk of injury.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Farmers are at high risk for fatal and nonfatal injuries (general traumatic injury and musculoskeletal injury), work-related lung diseases, noise-induced hearing loss, skin diseases, chemical-related illnesses, and certain cancers associated with chemical use and prolonged sun exposure.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In an average year, 516 workers die doing farm work in the U.S.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Every day, about 243 agricultural workers suffer lost-work-time injuries, and about 5% of these result in permanent impairment.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Tractor overturns are the leading cause of agriculture-related fatal injuries, and account for over 90 deaths every year.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health recommends the use of roll over protection structures on tractors to reduce the risk of overturn-related fatal injuries.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Farming is one of the few industries in which families (who often share the work and live on the premises) are also at risk for injuries, illness, and death.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Agriculture is the most dangerous industry for young workers, accounting for 42% of all work-related fatalities of young workers in the U.S. between 1992 and 2000.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In 2011, 108 youth, less than 20 years of age, died from farm-related injuries.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Unlike other industries, half the young victims in agriculture were under age 15.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] For young agricultural workers aged 15–17, the risk of fatal injury is four times the risk for young workers in other workplaces Agricultural work exposes young workers to safety hazards such as machinery, confined spaces, work at elevations, and work around livestock.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The most common causes of fatal farm-related youth injuries involve machinery, motor vehicles, or drowning.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Together these three causes comprise more than half of all fatal injuries to youth on U.S. farms.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Women in agriculture (including the related industries of forestry and fishing) numbered 556,000 in 2011.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] NIOSH CASH research centers are focused on the topic of health and safety in agricultural practices.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] These centers not only conduct research on the subject of occupational disease and injury prevention, but also promote agricultural health and safety through educational outreach programs.These groups funded by various state and federal agencies.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Farmers' suicides in the United States refers to the instances of American farmers taking their own lives, largely since the 1980s, partly due to their falling into debt, but mainly as a larger mental-health crisis among U.S. agriculture workers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In the Midwest alone, over 1,500 farmers have taken their own lives since the 1980s.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] It mirrors a crisis happening globally: in Australia, a farmer dies by suicide every ten days; in the United Kingdom, one farmer a week takes their own life; and in France it is one every two days.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Almost 300,000 farmers have died by suicide since 1995 in India.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Farmers are among the most likely to die by suicide, in comparison to other occupations, according to a study published in January 2020 by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Researchers at the University of Iowa found that farmers, and others in the agricultural trade, had the highest suicide rate of all occupations from 1992 to 2010, the years covered in a 2017 study.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The rate was 3.5 times that of the general population.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] This echoed a study conducted the previous year by the CDC and another undertaken by the National Rural Health Association (NRHA).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] As of April 2023, the suicide rate within the farming community exceeds that of the general population by three and a half times.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Agriculture in the U.S. makes up approximately 75% of the country's pesticide use.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Agricultural workers are at high risk for being exposed to dangerous levels of pesticides, whether or not they are directly working with the chemicals.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] For example, with issues like pesticide drift, farmworkers are not the only ones exposed to these chemicals; nearby residents come into contact with the pesticides as well.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The frequent exposure to these pesticides can have detrimental effects on humans, resulting in adverse health reactions associated with pesticide poisoning.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Migrant workers, especially women, are at higher risk for health issues associated with pesticide exposure due to lack of training or appropriate safety precautions.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] United States agricultural workers experience 10,000 cases or more of physician-diagnosed pesticide poisoning annually.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The application of agricultural chemicals provides a threat to drinking water quality.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Nitrate is a form of nitrogen found naturally in agricultural crops.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Nitrate-based fertilizer salts replenish depleted nutrients in croplands throughout the United States.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Drinking water contaminated with nitrate has been linked to methemoglobinemia, premature births, thyroid dysfunction, cancer, and cognitive impairment.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Heavy metals, such as lead, zinc, and copper, are naturally found in sedimentary and igneous rocks.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] One way humans introduce these metals is through agricultural practices.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Fertilizers containing phosphorus contribute to the amount of heavy metals in soils.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Pesticides also add heavy metals to soils, depending on their chemical formula and toxicity.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Heavy metal buildup in soils near bodies of water can contaminate drinking and recreational sources.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The aggregation of heavy metals via air, water, and food can be detrimental to bones, organs, and organ systems.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In children, exposure to lead, zinc, and copper can affect the nervous system.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Farmworkers are exposed to organophosphate insecticides by direct contact or inhalation from aerial application.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] A pregnant mother can pass organophosphates to an unborn baby, potentially causing abnormal birth deformities.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Prolonged exposure can lead to neurological complications in adults and delayed brain progression in children.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Neonicotinoid pesticides include Imidacloprid, clothianidin, and thiamethoxam, which are applied in liquid form.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] It is absorbed through the skin and can cause both nervous systems to deteriorate, an abnormal opening in the heart wall, and liver destruction.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The effects of agricultural contamination on low-income, marginalized communities has raised important environmental justice concerns.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Farm workers and communities of color, who often live near the farms where they work are more likely to be exposed to harmful chemicals, pesticides, and nitrate through direct contact, inhalation, or drinking water.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Many of these communities' source their drinking water from well water, that is at high risk of being contaminated with agricultural runoff, which can cause immediate and long-term health issues.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Inequities of ground water pollution are compounded in under served communities by economic and deeper structural factors.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Existing regulations in much of the United States, may not be adequate to control the contamination of ground water in these communities, especially those dependent on private well water, which does not require testing under the Safe Drinking Water Act.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Climate change and agriculture are complexly related processes.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In the United States, agriculture is the second largest emitter of greenhouse gases (GHG), behind the energy sector.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Direct GHG emissions from the agricultural sector account for 8.4% of total U.S. emissions, but the loss of soil organic carbon through soil erosion indirectly contributes to emissions as well.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] While agriculture plays a role in propelling climate change, it is also affected by the direct (increase in temperature, change in rainfall, flooding, drought) and secondary (weed, pest, disease pressure, infrastructure damage) consequences of climate change.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) is a regulatory, research, and support body in American agriculture.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] They work to understanding the impact of climate change on farming and to helping American farmers adapt.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] USDA research indicates that these climatic changes will lead to a decline in yield and nutrient density in key crops, as well as decreased livestock productivity.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Climate change poses unprecedented challenges to U.S. agriculture due to the sensitivity of agricultural productivity and costs to changing climate conditions.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Rural communities dependent on agriculture are particularly vulnerable to climate change threats.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Native communities are also vulnerable, and the Intertribal Agricultural Council (IAC) documents, supports, and advocates for the reintegrative practices of Native American and Alaskan agricultural producers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The IAC is particularly focused on the economic impact and potential of regenerative farming practices for native people.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The US Global Change Research Program (2017) identified four key areas of concern in the agriculture sector: reduced productivity, degradation of resources, health challenges for people and livestock, and the adaptive capacity of agriculture communities.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Large-scale adaptation and mitigation of these threats relies on changes in farming policy.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] This is 0.2% less than 2017 and varies based on state.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] It was highest in Arizona and Hawaii (48%).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Inequality and respect are common issues for these workers, as many have reported that they are not being respected, listened to, or taken seriously due to traditional views of women as housewives and caretakers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Women may also face resistance when attempting to advance to higher positions.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Other issues reported by female farm workers include receiving less pay than their male counterparts and a refusal or reluctance by their employers to offer their female workers the same additional benefits given to male workers such as housing.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In 2022, there were 46,738 African-American farmers in the United States, 4% less than 2017.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] This represents 1.4% of all U.S. farmers.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The vast majority of African-American farmers were in the south-eastern states.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] The state with the highest share of black farmers is Mississippi (12%).
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Historically, farmland has been owned by small property owners, but as of 2017 institutional investors, including foreign corporations, had been purchasing farmland.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In 2013 the largest producer of pork, Smithfield Foods, was bought by a company from China.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] As of 2017, only about 4% of farms have sales over $1m, but these farms yield two-thirds of total output.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Some of these are large farms have grown organically from private family-owned businesses.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] In the case of the meat-packing industry, large processing companies such as Tyson Foods, Hormel Foods and Pilgrim's Pride contract out to farmers to grow the chickens or then to then processing, package, and possibly market under their own brands.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] For example, in the 1960s, poultry processing companies experimented with owning and operating their own farms, but shifted away from it in later decades.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] As of 2019, six states—Hawaii, Iowa, Minnesota, Mississippi, North Dakota, and Oklahoma—have laws banning foreign ownership of farmland.
[src:agriculture-in-the-united-states/agriculture-in-the-united-states] Missouri, Ohio, and Oklahoma are looking to introduce bills banning foreign ownership as of 2019.
